my.net/tutorial-1-pattern-calculation-before-cutting/">Dress with Separately Cut Cups <span>(15)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="19"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-introductory-tutorial/">Bodysuit with Corset Cups <span>(9)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="24"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-measurement/">Party Dress <span>(17)</span></a></li></ul></li><li class="active">					<a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/categories/#544">Transparent corsets  <span>(4)</span></a><ul class="list-unstyled"><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="25"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-getting-acquainted-with-the-model-cutting-a-mock-up/">Corset with Drapery <span>(20)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="26"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-getting-acquainted-with-the-model-and-the-throw-over-sewing-technique/">Corset with Integral Straps <span>(27)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="34"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-getting-acquainted-with-the-model/">Corset with 3-Part Cups <span>(22)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="76"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-getting-acquainted-with-the-model-5/">Corset with a Fancy Cut-Out <span>(22)</span></a></li></ul></li><li class="active">					<a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/categories/#3082">Decoration Techniques  <span>(9)</span></a><ul class="list-unstyled"><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="83"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-decoration-materials/">Rhinestones Decoration <span>(5)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="84"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-glue-on-half-pearls/">Additional Decoration <span>(5)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="85"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-thick-decoration-element/">Thick Decoration Elements <span>(5)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="86"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-decoration-materials-2/">Wedding Dress Decoration <span>(5)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="87"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-types-of-sequins/">Sequins Decoration <span>(11)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="105"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-marking-the-borders-of-the-decoration/">Casual Garment Decoration <span>(5)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="106"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/epaulettes-function-and-materials/">Epaulettes <span>(8)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="127"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tambour-or-luneville-embroidery-part-1/">Tambour or Luneville Embroidery <span>(5)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="128"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/the-button-loop-closure-part-1/">The Button Loop Closure <span>(2)</span></a></li></ul></li><li class="active">					<a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/categories/#4289">Fancy Dresses for Girls  <span>(5)</span></a><ul class="list-unstyled"><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="118"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/childrens-body-proportions/">The Law of Proportions in Children's Wear <span>(3)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="117"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-choosing-a-suitable-style-for-the-childs-body-proportions/">Fancy Dress for 3 Years Old Girl <span>(9)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="119"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-choosing-a-suitable-dress/">Fancy Dress for 6 Years Old Girl <span>(16)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="120"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-choosing-a-suitable-style-with-respect-to-the-childs-body-proportions/">Fancy Dress for 9 Years Old Girl <span>(14)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="135"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-choosing-a-suitable-dress-with-regard-to-the-childs-body-proportions/">Fancy Dress for 12 Years Old Girl <span>(14)</span></a></li></ul></li>		</ul></div></div>													<div class="lesson-tab" role="tabpanel">				  <!-- Nav tabs -->				  <ul class="nav nav-tabs" role="tablist">					<li role="presentation" class="active"><a href="#about" aria-controls="about" role="tab" data-toggle="tab">Course details</a></li>																		<li role="presentation"><a href="#transcript" aria-controls="transcript" role="tab" data-toggle="tab">Transcript</a></li>														<li role="presentation"><a href="#pattern" aria-controls="pattern" role="tab" data-toggle="tab">Pattern</a></li>					<li role="presentation"><a href="#diploma" aria-controls="transcript" role="tab" data-toggle="tab">Diploma</a></li>						<li role="presentation"><a class="faq-tab blank" href="#faq" aria-controls="faq" role="tab" data-toggle="tab">FAQs</a></li>				  </ul>				  <!-- Tab panes -->				  <div class="tab-content">				  																									<div role="tabpanel" class="tab-pane active" id="about">											<div class="dark-get-started margin-0">																																											<p><strong>Dressmaker’s Treasury will equip you with a range of necessary tools and techniques which every professional must possess for successful work.</strong></p><p><strong>It will help you get more confident. You will know how to: </strong></p><ul><li>Choose the right strategy for making a garment after your first meeting with the client;</li><li>Take necessary measurements correctly and prepare and fill out an order form;</li><li>Choose the right basic pattern and adjust it after your client’s measurements with the help of automatic pattern adjustments calculation tables;</li><li>Avoid common mistakes which result in ill-fitting necklines by choosing the right sewing technique.</li></ul><p>&nbsp;</p><p><strong>The course&nbsp;is&nbsp;useful both to beginner dressmakers, as well as experienced professionals.</strong></p><p><strong>Author:</strong>&nbsp;Tatiana Kozorovitsky</p><p><strong>Total length:</strong>&nbsp;5h 16m</p>												</div>						</div>										<div role="tabpanel" class="tab-pane" id="transcript">						<div class="overlay"></div>						<!-- BEGIN Schema.org microdata added by the Add-Meta-Tags WordPress plugin --><!-- Scope BEGIN: Article --><div itemscope="" itemtype="http://schema.org/Article"><!-- Scope BEGIN: Organization --><span itemprop="publisher" itemscope="" itemtype="http://schema.org/Organization"><meta itemprop="name" content="Corset Academy"><!-- Scope BEGIN: ImageObject --><span itemprop="logo" itemscope="" itemtype="http://schema.org/ImageObject"><meta itemprop="name" content="Corset Academy logo"><meta itemprop="text" content="Corset Academy logo"><meta itemprop="url" content="https://corsetacademy.net/wp-content/themes/corset/img/logo.png"><meta itemprop="contentUrl" content="https://corsetacademy.net/wp-content/themes/corset/img/logo.png"><meta itemprop="width" content="303"><meta itemprop="height" content="49"><meta itemprop="encodingFormat" content="image/png"></span> <!-- Scope END: ImageObject --><meta itemprop="url" content="https://corsetacademy.net/"><meta itemprop="sameAs" content="https://www.facebook.com/corsetacademy"></span> <!-- Scope END: Organization --><!-- Scope BEGIN: Person --><span itemprop="author" itemscope="" itemtype="http://schema.org/Person"><meta itemprop="name" content="Tatiana Kozorovitsky"><!-- Scope BEGIN: ImageObject --><span itemprop="image" itemscope="" itemtype="http://schema.org/ImageObject"><meta itemprop="url" content="https://corsetacademy.net/wp-content/uploads/MVI_3285.MOV.00_00_31_09.Still001-128x128.jpg"><meta itemprop="contentUrl" content="https://corsetacademy.net/wp-content/uploads/MVI_3285.MOV.00_00_31_09.Still001-128x128.jpg"><meta itemprop="width" content="128"><meta itemprop="height" content="128"><meta itemprop="encodingFormat" content="image/jpeg"></span> <!-- Scope END: ImageObject --><meta itemprop="url" content="https://corsetacademy.net/author/infocorsetacademy-net/"><meta itemprop="sameAs" content="http://www.corsetacademy.net"></span> <!-- Scope END: Person --><meta itemprop="url" content="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-21-certain-properties-of-off-shoulder-sleeves/"><meta itemprop="mainEntityOfPage" content="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-21-certain-properties-of-off-shoulder-sleeves/"><meta itemprop="datePublished" content="2017-12-02T12:35:38+00:00"><meta itemprop="dateModified" content="2017-12-02T12:35:38+00:00"><meta itemprop="copyrightYear" content="2017"><meta itemprop="inLanguage" content="en_US"><meta itemprop="name" content="Tutorial 21. Certain Properties of Off-Shoulder Sleeves."><meta itemprop="headline" content="Tutorial 21. Certain Properties of Off-Shoulder Sleeves."><meta itemprop="description" content="In this tutorial, I want to talk about the type of sleeves known as off-shoulder, capless, or shoulderless sleeves"><meta itemprop="articleSection" content="Wedding and Evening Dresses. Theoretical Part."><meta itemprop="keywords" content="wedding and evening dresses. theoretical part., video"><!-- Scope BEGIN: ImageObject --><span itemprop="image" itemscope="" itemtype="http://schema.org/ImageObject"><meta itemprop="url" content="https://corsetacademy.net/wp-content/themes/corset/img/logo.png"><meta itemprop="contentUrl" content="https://corsetacademy.net/wp-content/themes/corset/img/logo.png"><meta itemprop="width" content="303"><meta itemprop="height" content="49"><meta itemprop="encodingFormat" content="image/png"></span> <!-- Scope END: ImageObject --><div itemprop="articleBody"><h1>Tutorial 21. Certain Properties of Off-Shoulder Sleeves.</h1><p><strong>In this tutorial, I want to talk about the type of sleeves known as off-shoulder, capless, or shoulderless sleeves. </strong></p><p><strong>This style has always been popular: </strong>girls like off-shoulder straps and boat-necks. Such garments are trending today thanks to the large available choice of high quality elastic lace and mesh fabrics.</p><p><strong>It used to be difficult to sew such garments </strong>because you couldn’t find suitable materials to make them graceful and beautiful. A lot has changed since those times.</p><p><strong>Elastic fabrics are available everywhere: </strong>you can find high-quality lace or mesh fabric, as well as various kinds of elastic silicone strips. The best invention is illusion mesh fabric which really allows you to work wonders, solve many fit-related tasks, and bring to life your clients’ most exclusive ideas!</p><p><strong>You must have guessed that I am talking about those outfits which feature a corset and a top with off-shoulder sleeves. </strong></p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%2021.files/image002.jpg" alt=""></p><p><strong>There are certain rules you need to know when sewing such garments. </strong>I am not surprised that beginners often experience problems when they sew such garments for the first time. Who said it would be easy? Do not get discouraged by misfortunes! Of course, there are garments which require a lot of technical understanding and practical experience, as well as correct choice of sewing materials! I believe 90% of success in the making of such garments depends on the correct choice of materials! You don’t need any special patterns or measurements for this purpose.</p><p><strong>There is a curious law in the making of such garments which every dressmaker must know and understand: </strong></p><p><strong>The higher the neckline of the top, the less elastic lace fabric it can be sewn with! </strong></p><p><strong>There is a simple explanation to this law: </strong>the higher the neckline of the top is, the larger area of it clings to the body helping the whole top hold in place better.</p><p><strong>But the lower the neckline is, the more elastic should the lace fabric be. </strong></p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%2021.files/image004.jpg" alt=""></p><p><strong>Most our clients prefer low-neck garments for their elegant look. </strong>And this means we need to use high-stretch lace fabrics for them. But we all know that high-stretch lace fabrics usually look the cheapest!</p><p>And yet our clients want a beautiful low neckline and fabulous exquisite lace at the same time!</p><p>If you and your client manage to find some beautiful one-of-a-kind lace fabric that does stretch and is dense and thick enough to hold its shape and let the wearer move her arms freely, then it will either cost a fortune or turn out to be non-stretch in the end.</p><p>I am talking about soutache lace, macramé lace, and lace fabrics with a generous amount of beautiful embroidery, beads, sequins, or pearls. Such kinds of lace hardly stretch at all!</p><p><strong>In cases like this, you can use illusion mesh – incredibly high-stretch and elastic nude mesh fabric which can support the entire construction on the wearer’s shoulders. </strong></p><p><strong><br><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%2021.files/image006.jpg" alt=""></strong></p><p><strong>Of course, illusion mesh is not the only solution of our problem. </strong></p><p>You can, for example, gather low-stretch lace fabric on a silicone tape. In this case, you must warn the client that there will be small gathers along the neckline of the top and on the sleeves, or else she will not be able to move her arms.</p><p><strong>And now, after this small foreword, let us talk about the technical side of sewing garments like this. </strong></p><p>It is easy enough to create a masterpiece with correctly chosen fabric!</p><p>And if the fabric does not meet all above-mentioned requirements, we will use illusion mesh fabric and other additional materials.</p><p><strong>You need to take additional measurements for the particular garment you want to sew before you get down to work. </strong></p><p>I purposely left out this type of garments when we were talking about measurements because I wanted to make a small foreword to avoid misunderstandings.</p><p><strong>Suppose a client has come and asked for a dress like this. </strong></p><p><strong>The first thing you should do is put an elastic band around her body at the supposed level of the top edge of the ready garment. </strong>Take careful note of the level where the elastic band passes along the chest, the arms, and the back.</p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%2021.files/image008.jpg" alt=""></p><p><strong>First of all, you should measure your client’s Aggregate Top Circumference. </strong>It is measured along the elastic band positioned at the supposed top edge level (arms included). Half-circumferences or quarter-circumferences will not do for this garment.</p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%2021.files/image010.jpg" alt=""></p><p><strong>Let me say a couple of words about the sleeves before we continue taking measurements. </strong>It is usually easier to make such garments based on a top made after a pattern of a corset with shoulders and with regular set-in sleeves. The distance from the top edge of the corset to the top edge of the top is normally not very big even when the corset has a rather low straight neckline.</p><p>It is my opinion that you should not make it overly complicated by using raglan sleeves. Regular set-in sleeves are more than appropriate.</p><p>Believe me, there is hardly any visible difference between raglan sleeves and plain set-in sleeves with that small distance. And the shape of the sleeve does not affect the convenience of movement.</p><p><strong>We can continue taking measurements. </strong></p><p><strong>Mark the position of the armscye at the front and at the back using a marker or pins. This is how you determine the part of the armscye to which the sleeve will be sewn. </strong></p><p><strong><br><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%2021.files/image012.jpg" alt=""></strong></p><p><strong>Then you measure and write down each separate section of the Aggregate Top Circumference: front length, length along the right arm, back length, length along the left arm. </strong></p><p><strong>Please make sure to measure the aggregate length across the back first</strong> and then check whether its middle coincides with the middle of your client’s spine. Very many women have scoliosis or spinal curvature so it is important to mark the actual place of the slit at the back of the dress either with respect to the corset or with respect to the spine. Choose what looks more aesthetically pleasing.</p><p><strong>Taking this into consideration, I recommend you should measure the left half and the right half of the back along the elastic band. </strong></p><p><strong>After you measure all sections of your client’s Aggregate Top Circumference, make sure to put the values together and check whether the total value coincides with the actual measurement. </strong></p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%2021.files/image014.jpg" alt=""></p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%2021.files/image016.jpg" alt=""></p><p><strong>Then, ask your client to put her hands on her waist. </strong>With this pose, the pins you put in the elastic band will move away from the armscye line.</p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%2021.files/image018.jpg" alt=""></p><p><strong>With your client standing this way, measure the distance between the pins across the front, the distance between the pins across the back, and the distance between the pins across either arm. </strong></p><p><strong>This will show you what areas at the top of the garment will stretch the most. </strong>You will be quite surprised to find out that the top edge of the garment stretches rather evenly (and even more at the front than on the sleeves).</p><p><strong>Thanks to such all-round even distribution, it is enough to gather thin delicate lace on a silicone tape without using illusion mesh fabric. </strong>Minor fullness can be re-distributed along the whole circumference to achieve maximum possible convenience of movement. The rest is easy!</p><p><strong>You should also remember to measure the distance between the top edge and the bust line. </strong></p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%2021.files/image020.jpg" alt=""></p><p><strong>Further algorithm of work is absolutely logical: </strong>you take a suitable pattern of a top, modify it by trimming away the excess above the bust line, adjust its armscye length, and construct the sleeve.</p><p><strong>Draw a horizontal cutting line on the sleeve cap (A-B). </strong></p><p><strong>The length of section A-B must be strictly the same as your client’s Arm Fullness. </strong>Make sure to check the stretch properties of this area to ensure proper freedom of movement for the arms.</p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%2021.files/image022.jpg" alt=""></p><p><strong>I recommend you put a see-through silicone tape along the top cutting line. </strong>It will secure the edge of the lace border and protect this area from getting stretched out.</p><p><strong>The silicone tape can be as long as the circumference or a couple of centimeters shorter </strong>to give the client a nice feeling of the dress hugging her shoulders.</p><p><strong>If you need to sew an entire top with illusion mesh fabric and imitate lace half-sleeves, </strong>then it is highly recommended that you lower the shoulder seams on the see-through part of the top and make them very thin to keep them unnoticeable. We don’t want to destroy the bare-shoulders effect.</p><p>When you look at the garment as a whole, those thin delicate see-through shoulder seams will be completely unnoticeable! It will look as if they were not there! As though the top edge of the dress simply clung to the body by itself. And it will not shift anywhere, the wearer will feel comfortable!</p><p><strong>In conclusion, let me remind you that side seam requirements remain the same even with off-shoulder sleeves, i.e. the side seam must be as long as possible! </strong>Then the sleeve and the arm in the sleeve will move freely. And the top edge of the dress hugging the arm will be fixed at the right level!</p></div> <!-- Itemprop END: articleBody --></div> <!-- Scope END: Article --><!-- END Schema.org microdata added by the Add-Meta-Tags WordPress plugin --> 					</div>															<div role="tabpanel" class="tab-pane" id="pattern">						<p>Sewing patterns are in PDF format.</p><p>To print sewing patterns open the files, press “print” and choose “<strong>PRINT IN ACTUAL SIZE</strong>“.</p><p>In each&nbsp;file the pattern is divided &nbsp;to A4 paper sheets for home printer.</p><a href="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/patterns/4%20curves%20corset%20-%20boat.pdf" target="_blank" class=""><img src="https://corsetacademy.net/wp-content/themes/corset-rs/img/pdf.